  <!-- ===== HERO ===== -->
  <section class="hero" style="padding-bottom: clamp(28px, 4vw, 56px);">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="hero__eyebrow">D1 · Survey + Dashboard</span>
      <h1 class="hero__title" style="font-size: clamp(2.25rem, 5.5vw, 4.25rem);">
        What fifteen marketing<br>
        practitioners <span class="accent">reported</span>.
      </h1>
      <p class="hero__lead">
        A two-layer evidence base for the project. Layer 1 maps Ontario auto
        insurance industry trends 2022–2025 from secondary sources. Layer 2
        reports a primary survey of marketing practitioners — familiarity,
        barriers, format preferences, privacy concerns, and outlook.
      </p>
      <div class="hero__meta">
        <span>Ontario, Canada</span>
        <span>N = 15</span>
        <span>Mar–Apr 2026</span>
        <span>APA 7</span>
      </div>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <a class="btn btn--primary" href="https://jade-salamander-5559d4.netlify.app" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open the live dashboard ↗</a>
        <a class="btn btn--ghost" href="./methodology.html">How the survey was built</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== EMBEDDED DASHBOARD (top of page, right after hero) ===== -->
  <section class="section section--accent" aria-labelledby="dash-h">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow" data-reveal>Live</span>
      <h2 id="dash-h" data-reveal data-delay="1">The two-layer dashboard</h2>
      <p class="lead" data-reveal data-delay="2">Layer 1 — Ontario industry data 2022–2025. Layer 2 — primary survey, N=15. Hosted on Netlify; opens in a new tab below or embedded here.</p>
      <div class="embed embed--tall" data-reveal data-delay="3" style="margin-top: 28px;">
        <iframe src="https://jade-salamander-5559d4.netlify.app" title="Digital Twins survey dashboard — D1" loading="lazy" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe>
      </div>
      <p style="margin-top: 16px;" data-reveal data-delay="4">
        <a class="btn btn--ghost" href="https://jade-salamander-5559d4.netlify.app" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open dashboard in new tab ↗</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== KPI ROW ===== -->
  <section class="section section--alt" aria-labelledby="kpi-h">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow" data-reveal>Primary survey · N=15 · Ontario · 2026</span>
      <h2 id="kpi-h" data-reveal data-delay="1">Headline numbers.</h2>
      <p class="lead" data-reveal data-delay="2">
        Four indicators that frame everything else on this page. Curiosity is
        high, practical understanding is low, and the preferred format for
        learning more is hands-on, not written.
      </p>

      <div class="kpi-grid" role="list" style="margin-top: 32px;">
        <div class="kpi" role="listitem" data-reveal data-delay="1">
          <p class="kpi__label"><span class="dot dot--build"></span> Q4 · awareness</p>
          <p class="kpi__num kpi__num--orange">73<span class="unit">%</span></p>
          <p class="kpi__desc">Have never heard of digital twins, or cannot explain the concept.</p>
          <span class="kpi__bar" style="--w: 73%;"></span>
        </div>
        <div class="kpi" role="listitem" data-reveal data-delay="2">
          <p class="kpi__label"><span class="dot dot--build"></span> Q6 · top barrier</p>
          <p class="kpi__num kpi__num--orange">60<span class="unit">%</span></p>
          <p class="kpi__desc">Name cost of implementation as the #1 adoption barrier.</p>
          <span class="kpi__bar" style="--w: 60%;"></span>
        </div>
        <div class="kpi" role="listitem" data-reveal data-delay="3">
          <p class="kpi__label"><span class="dot dot--build"></span> Q8 · format</p>
          <p class="kpi__num kpi__num--orange">80<span class="unit">%</span></p>
          <p class="kpi__desc">Prefer an interactive demo or simulator over written explainers.</p>
          <span class="kpi__bar" style="--w: 80%;"></span>
        </div>
        <div class="kpi" role="listitem" data-reveal data-delay="4">
          <p class="kpi__label"><span class="dot dot--live"></span> coverage</p>
          <p class="kpi__num">15<span class="unit">/15</span></p>
          <p class="kpi__desc">All practitioners completed the full instrument. Zero partial responses.</p>
          <span class="kpi__bar" style="--w: 100%;"></span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== BREAKDOWNS — bar rows per question ===== -->
  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="break-h">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow" data-reveal>Question-by-question</span>
      <h2 id="break-h" data-reveal data-delay="1">The seven questions, decoded.</h2>
      <p class="lead" data-reveal data-delay="2">
        Each block below is one survey question with a one-line interpretation
        and the response distribution as a bar row. Percentages are based on
        <code>N=15</code>; rows under 7% are omitted.
      </p>

      <!-- Q4 -->
      <article style="margin-top: 36px;">
        <h3>Q4 · Have you heard of digital twin technology?</h3>
        <p>Awareness is shallow. Nearly three-quarters of respondents sit in the bottom two tiers — never heard of it, or heard the term but cannot explain it.</p>
        <div class="bar-row">
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 47%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Heard the term but cannot explain</span>
            <span class="bar__value">47%</span>
          </div>
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 27%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Have never heard of digital twins</span>
            <span class="bar__value">27%</span>
          </div>
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 20%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Can explain at a basic level</span>
            <span class="bar__value">20%</span>
          </div>
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 7%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Can explain in detail / have used in work</span>
            <span class="bar__value">7%</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Q6 -->
      <article style="margin-top: 48px;">
        <h3>Q6 · Barriers to adoption (multi-select)</h3>
        <p>Cost is the runaway #1. Two of the next three barriers are also commercial — unclear ROI and lack of talent — suggesting the conversation needs to move from "what is it" to "what does it pay back" before adoption gets serious.</p>
        <div class="bar-row">
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 60%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Cost of implementation</span>
            <span class="bar__value">60%</span>
          </div>
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 53%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Unclear ROI</span>
            <span class="bar__value">53%</span>
          </div>
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 47%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Lack of in-house talent / skills</span>
            <span class="bar__value">47%</span>
          </div>
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 40%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Data privacy &amp; regulatory concerns</span>
            <span class="bar__value">40%</span>
          </div>
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 33%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Integration with legacy systems</span>
            <span class="bar__value">33%</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Q7 -->
      <article style="margin-top: 48px;">
        <h3>Q7 · Confidence explaining digital twins to a colleague</h3>
        <p>Two-thirds report they are not, or only slightly, confident they could explain a digital twin to a colleague. This is the gap a long-read or simulator is meant to close.</p>
        <div class="bar-row">
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 40%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Slightly confident</span>
            <span class="bar__value">40%</span>
          </div>
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 27%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Not at all confident</span>
            <span class="bar__value">27%</span>
          </div>
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 20%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Moderately confident</span>
            <span class="bar__value">20%</span>
          </div>
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 13%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Very / extremely confident</span>
            <span class="bar__value">13%</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Q8 -->
      <article style="margin-top: 48px;">
        <h3>Q8 · Preferred format for learning about the technology</h3>
        <p>Demonstrations beat documentation. Eighty percent picked an interactive demo or simulator — the strongest single signal in the dataset, and the direct rationale for D3.</p>
        <div class="bar-row">
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 80%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Interactive demo / simulator</span>
            <span class="bar__value">80%</span>
          </div>
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 47%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Short video / podcast</span>
            <span class="bar__value">47%</span>
          </div>
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 33%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Long-read article / zine</span>
            <span class="bar__value">33%</span>
          </div>
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 27%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Slide deck / one-pager</span>
            <span class="bar__value">27%</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- Q9 -->
      <article style="margin-top: 48px;">
        <h3>Q9 · Importance of data privacy to engagement</h3>
        <p>Privacy is not a soft preference — it is a precondition. Nearly three-quarters rate it "very important" or "critical." Any artifact that demos personalization must address consent and data scope up front.</p>
        <div class="bar-row">
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 47%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Very important</span>
            <span class="bar__value">47%</span>
          </div>
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 27%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Critical / dealbreaker if mishandled</span>
            <span class="bar__value">27%</span>
          </div>
          <div class="bar" style="--w: 20%;">
            <span class="bar__label">Moderately important</span>
            <span class="bar__value">20%</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== LAYER 1 — industry data ===== -->
  <section class="section section--alt" aria-labelledby="layer1-h">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow" data-reveal>Layer 1 · Industry context</span>
      <h2 id="layer1-h" data-reveal data-delay="1">What the secondary record says.</h2>
      <p class="lead" data-reveal data-delay="2">
        The practitioner survey sits on top of an industry layer drawn from
        regulatory filings, telematics vendor reports, and trade publications
        2022–2025. The directional reading: telematics-adjacent
        personalization is moving from pilot to platform, but published
        Canadian numbers remain sparse and methodologically uneven.
      </p>

      <table class="meta-table" style="margin-top: 24px;">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Year</th>
            <th>Indicator</th>
            <th>Source category</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td class="mono">2022</td>
            <td>Telematics / UBI offered by at least one major Ontario insurer; voluntary opt-in only.</td>
            <td>FSRA / regulatory documents</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="mono">2023</td>
            <td>Digital-twin terminology enters North American insurance trade press; framed mostly via underwriting use cases.</td>
            <td>Industry trade publications</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="mono">2024</td>
            <td>Mature digital-twin practice documented in adjacent industries (Siemens, GE, Microsoft, Mayo Clinic, Tesla) — referenced as the analog for insurance personalization.</td>
            <td>Peer-reviewed papers + vendor reports</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="mono">2025</td>
            <td>Personalization framed as the wedge use case for insurance, but published Canadian deployment numbers remain sparse.</td>
            <td>Professional publications</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p class="muted" style="margin-top: 18px; font-size: var(--fs-sm);">
        Full source list with one-line annotations on the <a href="./resources.html">reading list</a>. Real-world deployment cases on the <a href="./cases.html">cases page</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== READ THE RAW DATA — softened note ===== -->
  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="query-h">
    <div class="container container-narrow">
      <span class="eyebrow" data-reveal>Reading the raw data</span>
      <h2 id="query-h" data-reveal data-delay="1">A note on what the numbers do and don't say.</h2>

      <div class="terminal">
        <div class="terminal__head">Sample readings · D1</div>
        <div class="terminal__body">
          <p>Filtering Q4 responses for the "cannot explain" tier returns 11 of 15 records, or 73.3% of the sample.</p>
          <p>Filtering Q8 responses for "interactive demo / simulator" as the preferred format returns 12 of 15 records, or 80.0%.</p>
          <p>The raw responses sheet is read-only and linked from the methodology card inside the dashboard.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <blockquote class="pullquote">
        N=15 is too small to generalize to "Ontario insurance marketing" as a
        population. The percentages are descriptive of who answered, not
        predictive of who didn't.
      </blockquote>
      <p>
        Recruitment was multi-channel (warm introductions, LinkedIn DMs, four
        Facebook groups), so each channel likely brings a different selection
        bias. The cost-of-implementation finding (60%) is the result that
        appears most stable at this sample size; the others may shift with a
        larger sample. See the <a href="./methodology.html">methodology page</a>
        for the supervisor-iteration trace and full limitations.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== SUCCESS CRITERIA ===== -->
  <section class="section section--alt" aria-labelledby="d1-success-h">
    <div class="container container-narrow">
      <span class="eyebrow" data-reveal>What "working" looks like for D1</span>
      <h2 id="d1-success-h" data-reveal data-delay="1">Success criteria — Survey &amp; Dashboard.</h2>
      <p class="lead" data-reveal data-delay="2">
        Directional thresholds. Not statistical claims — the lines below
        which this artifact would be accepted as not doing its job.
      </p>

      <div class="success" style="margin-top: 28px;">
        <h3>D1 · Survey + Dashboard</h3>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Capability shift:</strong> measurable reduction in the share of respondents in the "cannot explain" tier between baseline and any follow-up wave.</li>
          <li><strong>Engagement:</strong> ≥40% of dashboard visitors scroll to the methodology section.</li>
          <li><strong>Trust:</strong> at least 1 substantive citation or share by an industry peer between 2026-05 and 2026-06.</li>
          <li><strong>Coverage:</strong> dashboard load time under 3 seconds on cable-grade connection; all charts render with no console errors.</li>
        </ol>
        <p class="muted" style="margin-top: 16px; font-size: var(--fs-sm);">
          Per-artifact criteria for D2–D6 are on the <a href="./methodology.html#success">methodology page</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="citation" style="margin-top: 32px;">
        Suggested citation (APA 7):<br>
        Okhrimenko, A. (2026). <em>Digital twin awareness in Ontario auto insurance marketing: A two-layer evidence dashboard</em> [Capstone deliverable, University of Niagara Falls Canada]. Retrieved from this site.
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</main>

